# Git + GitHub Deploy Workflow

A personal reference for editing and deploying a blog via GitHub Actions.

---

## How it works

```
GitHub Repo → clone to PC → edit in VS Code → git push → auto deploy ✅
```

---

## First-time setup (do this once only)

### 1. Clone the repo to your PC

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/your-blog-repo.git
```

This downloads the entire repo into a folder on your computer.

### 2. Open the folder in VS Code

```bash
cd your-blog-repo
code .
```

> Or drag the folder into VS Code manually.

---

## Every editing session

### Step 1 — Pull the latest changes before you start

```bash
git pull origin main
```

### Step 2 — Edit your files

| File | What to edit |
|------|-------------|
| `style.css` | Colours, fonts, layout tweaks |
| `index.html` | Page structure and content |

Save with `Ctrl + S` as usual.

### Step 3 — Push your changes

Open the terminal in VS Code with `` Ctrl + ` `` (backtick), then run:

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "describe what you changed"
git push origin main
```

### Step 4 — Watch the deploy

Go to your repo on GitHub → **Actions** tab.  
GitHub Actions triggers automatically and your live site updates in **~1–2 minutes**.

---

## Full session in one block (copy-paste ready)

```bash
# Before editing
git pull origin main

# After editing
git add .
git commit -m "your message here"
git push origin main
```

---

## VS Code shortcut (no terminal needed)

Use the **Source Control panel** (branch icon on the left sidebar) to:
- Stage files (the `+` button)
- Write a commit message
- Click **Commit** then **Sync / Push**

No commands required — just clicking buttons.

---

## Quick glossary

| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `git clone` | Download a repo to your PC for the first time |
| `git pull` | Sync your local copy with the latest from GitHub |
| `git add .` | Stage all changed files, ready to commit |
| `git commit -m "..."` | Save a snapshot of your changes with a message |
| `git push` | Upload your commits to GitHub |
| GitHub Actions | Auto-runs deploy script when you push to `main` |

